Day 17: Navigation using useNavigate()

So far, you've used Link for navigation:

<Link to="/about">About</Link>

But sometimes you need to navigate programmatically after an action such as:

Login success
Form submission
Button click
API response
Logout

For that, React Router provides useNavigate().

What is useNavigate()?

useNavigate() is a hook used to navigate to another route from JavaScript code.

import { useNavigate } from "react-router-dom";
Basic Example
Home.jsx
import { useNavigate } from "react-router-dom";

function Home() {
    const navigate = useNavigate();

    return (
        <div>
            <h2>Home Page</h2>

            <button onClick={() => navigate("/about")}>
                Go to About
            </button>
        </div>
    );
}

export default Home;
Result

Clicking the button takes you to:

/about
Example 2: Navigation After Login
Login.jsx
import { useState } from "react";
import { useNavigate } from "react-router-dom";

function Login() {
    const [username, setUsername] = useState("");
    const navigate = useNavigate();

    const handleLogin = () => {
        if (username === "admin") {
            navigate("/dashboard");
        }
    };

    return (
        <div>
            <input
                value={username}
                onChange={(e) => setUsername(e.target.value)}
                placeholder="Username"
            />

            <button onClick={handleLogin}>
                Login
            </button>
        </div>
    );
}

export default Login;
Example 3: Passing Route Parameters
import { useNavigate } from "react-router-dom";

function Users() {
    const navigate = useNavigate();

    return (
        <div>
            <button onClick={() => navigate("/user/101")}>
                User 101
            </button>

            <button onClick={() => navigate("/user/102")}>
                User 102
            </button>
        </div>
    );
}

export default Users;
Go Back

Navigate to the previous page:

navigate(-1);

Example:

<button onClick={() => navigate(-1)}>
    Back
</button>

Works like the browser Back button.

Go Forward
navigate(1);

Example:

<button onClick={() => navigate(1)}>
    Forward
</button>
Replace Current History Entry

Normally:

navigate("/home");

adds a history entry.

To replace the current page:

navigate("/home", { replace: true });

Useful after login/logout.

Complete Example
App.jsx
import { BrowserRouter, Routes, Route } from "react-router-dom";
import Home from "./Home";
import About from "./About";

function App() {
    return (
        <BrowserRouter>
            <Routes>
                <Route path="/" element={<Home />} />
                <Route path="/about" element={<About />} />
            </Routes>
        </BrowserRouter>
    );
}

export default App;
